1. TreeKEM Sufficiency for Adversarial Forward Secrecy
Short answer: Yes, but with caveats.
Your TreeKEM implementation is the right architectural choice. Here's why it matters:
What You Get Right

O(log N) updates: When Alice leaves, you only re-key log(N) nodes in the binary tree, not broadcast new keys to every remaining member
Post-compromise security: If an attacker compromises one member's state, they don't automatically get future keys after a tree update
Group scalability: This is why Wire uses TreeKEM and why MLS exists

The Adversarial Concern
The weakness isn't TreeKEM itself—it's the trustless relay + TreeKEM combination:
Problem: Your relay can correlate tree update patterns
Scenario:
- Alice leaves room X at 14:23:15
- Relay sees N encrypted TreeKEM update messages immediately after
- Relay now knows: "Room X has N members, Alice probably left"
Mitigations you should consider:

Padding: Pad all TreeKEM updates to a fixed size (e.g., always send enough noise packets to look like a 32-member update, regardless of actual tree size)
Scheduled updates: Don't update immediately on leave—batch updates every T seconds with dummy updates if needed
Dummy traffic: Periodically send fake "member left" updates with random tree reshuffles

Verdict: TreeKEM is cryptographically sound. Your threat model weakness is metadata leakage through timing/frequency, not the protocol itself.

2. Double Ratchet Overhead at High Frequency
This is your most legitimate performance concern.
The Math
javascript// Per-operation cost:
HKDF-SHA256:  ~0.03ms  (key derivation)
AES-GCM enc:  ~0.02ms  (encryption)
TOTAL:        ~0.05ms per operation
At 60fps canvas sync (60 ops/sec), you're at 3ms/sec crypto overhead (6% of frame budget). This is fine.
But here's where it breaks:
The Real Bottleneck: Not Crypto, But MessagePack + Network RTT
Actual performance killers:

Serialization: MessagePack encoding of CRDT operations + metadata
Network round-trip: Even WebRTC has 20-50ms P2P latency
CRDT merge: Inserting into RGA with causal dependencies

Recommendations
For 60fps use cases (canvas/cursors), use two-tier architecture:
javascript// Tier 1: Ephemeral awareness (NO CRDT, NO ENCRYPTION)
awareness.setCursor({ x: 150, y: 200 })  // Sent in plaintext, high frequency
// Rational: Cursor position has zero long-term value to attackers

// Tier 2: Persistent operations (CRDT + Double Ratchet)
doc.insert(5, "hello")  // Full crypto, lower frequency
You're already doing this with AwarenessProtocol (per your architecture diagram), which is correct.
For canvas drawing at 60fps:

Option A: Batch strokes—only commit the final polyline to the CRDT after pen-up
Option B: Use a conflict-free canvas CRDT (like LSEQ or Logoot) with coarser granularity (stroke-level, not point-level)

Verdict: Double Ratchet overhead is negligible for typical collaboration (typing, drawing, data updates). Your concern should be when to use ephemeral vs. persistent sync, not crypto cost.

