javascript// In your RichText CRDT:
const MARK_TYPES = {
  bold: { nestable: true, priority: 1 },
  italic: { nestable: true, priority: 1 },
  link: { nestable: false, priority: 2 },  // Links can't nest
  comment: { nestable: false, priority: 3 }, // Comments supersede links
}

// When applying marks, filter by nestability + priority
applyMark(elemId, mark) {
  const existing = this.getMarks(elemId);
  if (!MARK_TYPES[mark].nestable && existing.some(m => m.type === mark)) {
    // Reject or replace
  }
}
Verdict: Your element-ID approach is 90% of the value at 20% of the complexity. Peritext is only necessary if you need:

Collaborative comments (non-nestable, must split)
Complex mark semantics (e.g., strikethrough supersedes bold)
Predictable mark expansion rules for power users

Stick with your approach unless users complain about "weird formatting behavior."

