Solution: Time-Windowed Deduplication
javascriptclass ReplayProtection {
  constructor() {
    this.recentOpIds = new Map(); // opId → timestamp
    this.CACHE_WINDOW = 7 * 86400 * 1000; // 7 days
  }
  
  validate(op) {
    // Check 1: Recent opId cache (7-day window)
    if (this.recentOpIds.has(op.opId)) {
      const age = Date.now() - this.recentOpIds.get(op.opId);
      if (age < this.CACHE_WINDOW) {
        throw new ReplayError('Duplicate opId');
      }
    }
    
    // Check 2: Lamport clock (permanent)
    if (op.clock <= this.clock.get(op.nodeId)) {
      throw new ReplayError('Stale clock');
    }
    
    // Accept and cache
    this.recentOpIds.set(op.opId, Date.now());
    this.clock.set(op.nodeId, op.clock);
  }
  
  prune() {
    // Remove opIds older than window
    for (const [opId, timestamp] of this.recentOpIds) {
      if (Date.now() - timestamp > this.CACHE_WINDOW) {
        this.recentOpIds.delete(opId);
      }
    }
  }
  
  serialize() {
    // Only serialize recent opIds (bounded size)
    return {
      clocks: this.clock.serialize(),
      recentOpIds: Array.from(this.recentOpIds.entries()),
    };
  }
}
Rationale:

Replay attacks are only viable within a time window (e.g., 7 days)
After 7 days, operation is "expired" and won't be accepted anyway
Lamport clock still provides primary replay protection

Recommendation: Implement time-windowed opId cache with configurable retention period.

